{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525902"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:18:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:18:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14100"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14100"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.37,0.31,0.06,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6770"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6770"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1200"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4998"},{"type":"tags","id":"5967"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46025"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up ten days after starting therapeutic trimethoprim\u2013sulfamethoxazole for \u003Cem\u003EStenotrophomonas maltophilia\u003C/em\u003E pneumonia. She commenced treatment for acute myeloid leukaemia with venetoclax and azacitidine one month ago. She reports improved cough and breathlessness over the past week and has had no fever, rash, pruritus, loin pain, or reduced urine output. She denies non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug use and has not had intravascular contrast. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, being treated with extended-release metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 132/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Chest examination is clear, and there is no peripheral oedema or rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations today reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eserum creatinine 102 \u00b5mol/L (45\u201390)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eserum urea 5.4 mmol/L (2.5\u20136.7)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eestimated glomerular filtration rate 52 mL/min/1.73 m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eserum potassium 4.6 mmol/L (3.5\u20135.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eurinalysis showing no blood, no protein, no leucocytes, and no nitrites\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer creatinine one month ago (prior to antibiotic treatment) was 75 \u00b5mol/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the rise in serum creatinine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Progression of chronic kidney disease","Inhibition of tubular creatinine secretion","Acute interstitial nephritis","Metformin accumulation","Acute tubular necrosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETrimethoprim\u2013sulfamethoxazole can increase measured serum creatinine by inhibiting tubular secretion of creatinine via organic cation transporters. This effect occurs within days of starting therapy, is reversible on cessation, and does not reflect a true decline in glomerular filtration. Recognising this prevents unnecessary cessation of effective therapy for suspected \u003Cem\u003EStenotrophomonas maltophilia\u003C/em\u003E pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of tubular creatinine secretion\u003C/strong\u003E best fits the findings: the rise appeared within two weeks of drug initiation, the person feels well, urinalysis is bland, serum urea is within the reference interval, potassium is not elevated, and there are no haemodynamic or volume concerns. This discordance between creatinine and clinical status is typical of a pseudo-worsening of kidney function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgression of chronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the abrupt change from a previously normal creatinine, absence of known kidney disease, and the clear temporal association with starting trimethoprim.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute interstitial nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E from antibiotics often presents with systemic features such as fever, rash, arthralgia, eosinophilia, and urinary abnormalities like haematuria or sterile pyuria, none of which are present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin accumulation\u003C/strong\u003E does not cause an increase in creatinine; rather, it can occur secondary to reduced kidney function and may present with gastrointestinal symptoms or lactic acidosis, which are not described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute tubular necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E would more typically follow hypotension, sepsis, or nephrotoxin exposure and often shows larger creatinine rises with possible oliguria and urinary sediment abnormalities; these features are absent, and the timing with trimethoprim points away from this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trimethoprim\u2013sulfamethoxazole can cause a reversible rise in serum creatinine by inhibiting tubular secretion without reducing true glomerular filtration.","A discordant rise in creatinine with stable urea and bland urinalysis during trimethoprim therapy suggests pseudo-worsening of kidney function rather than intrinsic kidney injury.","Link changes in kidney indices to drug timing, clinical stability, and urine findings to distinguish drug effect from acute kidney injury."],"references":["Delanaye P, Mariat C, Cavalier E, Maillard N, Krzesinski JM, White CA. Trimethoprim, creatinine and creatinine-based equations. Nephron Clin Pract. 2011;119(3):c187-93; discussion c193-4. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21832843/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14100"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94400"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-30T13:18:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-30T13:18:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6770"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112352"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"a